- In the previous page, the main problem was **manual object management**.
- Spring Boot solves this by taking control of **object creation and dependency writng**.

---

**Project Structure**
```SSS
demo
└─ src
   └─ main
      └─ java/com/example/demo/service
         ├─ OrderService.java
         ├─ PaymentServiceInterface.java
         ├─ UPIPaymentService.java
      └─ DemoApplication.java
```
`service` → Contains all business logic and payment services. \
`DemoApplication.java` → Main Spring Boot application.

---

**1: Payment Interface : \
**`PaymentServiceInterface.java`****

```java
public interface PaymentServiceInterface {
    void pay();
}
```

The interface defines **what** a payment is, not **how** it is done (No implementation details).

---

**2: Payment Implementation (Single Service) :** \
**`UPIPaymentService.java`**

```java
@Service
public class UPIPaymentService implements PaymentServiceInterface {

    @Override
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Payment done using UPI");
    }
}
```

Here:

* There is **only one implementation** of `PaymentServiceInterface `
* Spring Boot can easily decide which object to create
* No extra configuration is required

**`@Service`** tells Spring Boot: \
**“Create and manage an object of this class.**”

---

**3: `OrderService.java`(No `new` Keyword)**
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {

    private final PaymentServiceInterface paymentService;

    // Constructor Injection
    public OrderService(PaymentServiceInterface paymentService) {
        this.paymentService = paymentService;
    }

    public void placeOrder() {
        paymentService.pay();
        System.out.println("Order placed");
    }
}
```

Here:

* `OrderService` does NOT create `new PaymentService()`
* Spring Boot injects `UPIPaymentService` automatically
* This is **Dependency Injection**

Because there is only one Payment Service, Spring knows exactly what to inject.

---

**4: Application Entry Point :**
**`DemoApplication.java`**
```java
@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApplication implements CommandLineRunner {

    private final OrderService orderService;

    public DemoApplication(OrderService orderService) {
        this.orderService = orderService;
    }

    @Override
    public void run(String... args) {
        orderService.placeOrder();
    }
}
```

- No `new OrderService()`
- No `if-else`

**Spring Boot does everything.**

---

**Run the Application - You'll see below output:**
```sss
Payment done using UPI
Order placed
```

